Zhejiang Medicine Co. Ltd. | Asia Pacific 2Q25: Still Benefiting from Vitamin Prices
Unchanged Impact to our thesis
In- line Financial results versus consensus
Largely unchanged Direction of next 12- month consensus EPS
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research
Zhejiang reported 1H25 revenue and earnings of Rmb4,323mn (- 1.9% YoY) and Rmb673mn (+113.5% YoY), which were 10% and 3% below our estimates.
Note that a net profit range was announced in mid- July. The above translates to 2Q25 revenue and earnings of Rmb2,067mn (- 4.1% YoY) and Rmb264mn (+28.5% YoY).
The nutrition segment is still benefitting from higher vitamin prices YoY, an aftereffect of global supply disruption caused by a fire at BASF's German plant.

Supply did not appear to have fully stabilized as of 2Q25: A fire broke out at BASF's Ludwigshafen plant in July 2024, causing a global shortage of precursors for vitamins A and E and creating a windfall for Chinese manufacturers (note). As shown in Exhibit 1, Chinese export prices rose sharply in the months following the incident. In 1Q25, BASF set a tentative schedule of resuming production by mid- 2025 (note). BASF's latest commentary (covered by Thomas Wrigglesworth) indicated that it was burdened with ramp- up costs associated with restart of the vitamins business (note). In 1H25, Zhejiang's nutrition segment revenue was up 0.6% YoY, but segment gross margin expanded 15.4ppt YoY to 55.0%. China customs data are consistent with these trends. In 1H25, average export prices of vitamins A and E were up 9% and 76% YoY to Rmb92/kg and Rmb119/kg, but export tonnage declined 5% and 16% YoY.

The formulations segment showed weaker trends: 1H25 revenue declined 5.2% YoY to Rmb2,223mn. Segment gross margin contracted 5.8ppt YoY to 26.6%, due to centralized procurement price cuts and high costs of APIs.
Source: Wind, Morgan Stanley Research.
Source: China Customs, Morgan Stanley Research.

Our price target is derived from discounted cash flow, assuming an \(8.8\%\) cost of equity, \(4\%\) terminal growth rate, \(12\%\) long- term ROE on new investments, and \(30\%\) net debt- to- equity ratio.
Prolonged global supply shortage; Strong clinical data from its oncology biologics; New product launches, e.g. next- generation antibiotics.
Full resumption of European supply for vitamins; Price competition from domestic producers; Drastic price cuts on antibiotics in China by the government.
